- lib_jobs_TypeScript.prompt — provides `getJob`
- lib_sse_TypeScript.prompt — provides `createSseStream`

Instructions
- Use Next.js App Router dynamic route: `export async function GET(request: Request, { params }: { params: { id: string } })`.
- SSE polling pattern: inside `ReadableStream.start(controller)`, use `setInterval` (200ms) to poll `getJob(params.id)`.
- Track `lastLineIndex` in closure; split `job.logs` on newline; send only new lines.
- Clear interval when job reaches `done` or `error` status, then close the controller.
- If job is not found on first poll, send `event: error\ndata: {"message":"Job not found"}\n\n` and close.
- Return `new Response(stream, { headers: { 'Content-Type': 'text/event-stream', 'Cache-Control': 'no-cache', 'Connection': 'keep-alive' } })`.

Deliverable
- `app/api/jobs/[id]/stream/route.ts` — SSE GET handler for real-time job progress streaming.

Note: The following endpoints are in SEPARATE route files (not in this file):
- `GET /api/jobs/[id]` → `app/api/jobs/[id]/route.ts`
- `POST /api/jobs/[id]/retry` → `app/api/jobs/[id]/retry/route.ts`

Implementation assumptions (explicit)
- Job logs are persisted to the `jobs.logs` TEXT column as newline-delimited text.
- Client `SseLogPanel` falls back to polling `/api/jobs/[id]` if EventSource fails.
- The interval is cleared on stream close to prevent DB polling leaks.

Please produce production-ready TypeScript code consistent with the above.
